## A.2 Graph Taxonomy (Three Distinct Types)

```
TYPE 1: CHUNK GRAPHS
  - Created: during prompt normalization, one per chunk
  - Stored: separately, persist as historical/archived evidence
  - Purpose: AMT uses these as evidence for intent extraction
  - Contains: chunk root node, keyword nodes, entity nodes, topic nodes,
              grammar relationship edges, modality reference nodes
  - Lifecycle: Created → archived (never discarded)
  - Smart reconstruction: since we store span positions (start_char, end_char)
    and full grammar relationships/sentence boundaries, chunks can be
    reconstructed at ANY token limit for any downstream LLM. This makes
    the system cross-model capable.

TYPE 2: MODALITY GRAPHS
  - Created: during initial graph creation (Phase 2), one per modality
  - Stored: in /ModalityGraphs/ per project (separate from chunk graphs)
  - Purpose: The primary knowledge representation for each modality domain
  - Contains: Root node (with detection metadata) + full domain graph
  - Lifecycle: Created → Structural → SemanticEnriched → CrossLinked →
               Stable → Updated (by step execution) → ReValidating
  - Root node IS the root hierarchy — no separate "detection graph"

TYPE 3: AMT TREE
  - Created: during AMT building (Phase 3)
  - Stored: in /AMT/ per session
  - Purpose: Intent decomposition, drives blueprint creation
  - Contains: intent nodes, methodology references, graph node citations
  - Lifecycle: Built layer by layer → stable → referenced during execution
```

## A.3 Smart Chunking System

Chunks are not static slices. The system derives a full structural model of the prompt during normalization, enabling **dynamic reconstruction at any token limit**:

```
SMART CHUNKING DESIGN

Original Prompt (full text)
  └── Chunk Graph (per chunk)
        ├── start_char: 0      ← exact position in original prompt
        ├── end_char: 4096
        ├── sentence_starts: [0, 124, 267, ...]    ← derived from grammar pass
        ├── sentence_ends: [123, 266, 412, ...]
        ├── paragraph_breaks: [267, 891, ...]
        ├── keyword_nodes: [...]
        ├── grammar_rels: [...]
        └── modality_refs: [...]

RECONSTRUCTION AT ANY TOKEN LIMIT:
  Given: target_token_limit, model_id, step_context
  1. Query chunk graphs for relevant span ranges
  2. Use sentence_starts/ends to find clean boundaries at target limit
  3. Reconstruct clean text from original prompt positions
  4. No re-chunking LLM call needed — all structural data already derived

CROSS-MODEL CAPABILITY:
  - GPT-4 (128k context): reconstruct with large token limit
  - Claude Haiku (200k): reconstruct with different limit
  - Local 7B (4k): reconstruct minimal context
  All from the same chunk graph data — one normalization pass serves all.
```

