## B.4 EdgeProvenance — REDESIGNED (Source-Object Based)

EdgeProvenance answers: **"What object was this edge derived from?"** — not how it was inferred. The derivation method is implicit in the processing phase.

```rust
/// EdgeProvenance identifies the SOURCE OBJECT that this edge was derived from.
/// This enables full traceability back to the original data.
#[derive(Debug, Clone, Serialize, Deserialize, Default)]
pub enum EdgeProvenance {
    #[default]
    Unknown,

    // SOURCE OBJECT TYPES
    DerivedFromPrompt,          // edge came from analyzing the original prompt
    DerivedFromChunk(u32),      // edge came from chunk at index N
    DerivedFromChunkGraph(u64), // edge came from chunk graph ID N
    DerivedFromModalityGraph(u64), // edge derived from another modality graph
    DerivedFromFile(String),    // edge derived from attached file (path/name)
    DerivedFromAMT,             // edge derived from AMT tree analysis
    DerivedFromBlueprint(u32),  // edge derived from blueprint step N
    DerivedFromMethodology(u64),// edge derived from methodology application
    DerivedFromCrossModal,      // edge derived from cross-modality analysis
    DerivedFromHook,            // edge derived from ZSEI semantic hook

    // VERSIONING ORIGINS
    VersionOf(u32),             // this is version N of the original edge
    ForkedFrom(u64),            // forked from edge ID N
}
```

**DerivedFrom hierarchy note:** Most `DerivedFrom` variants will be hierarchical by nature — e.g., DerivedFromChunk(3) implies DerivedFromPrompt transitively. The system stores the most proximate source, not the full chain. Full chain is reconstructible by traversing DerivedFrom edges.

